threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB shared object, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, BuildID[sha1]=e322f65300f4cc76f6fc0ef39eeea75b7338ba24, not stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This sample is a backdoor that provides remote access to a compromised system. It listens for incoming connections on TCP port 10289. Once connected, it offers functionalities including remote shell execution, file upload/download, and port forwarding. Command and control (C2) communications are encrypted using AES and authenticated with SHA1. A key malicious behavior is spawning a bash shell (`/bin/bash`) while masquerading the process name as a legitimate system service (`/usr/sbin/modem-manager`) to evade detection. It also disables shell history logging by unsetting the HISTFILE environment variable.
